# Hypothesis

## Core Hypothesis

Temporally structured excitation combined with passive phase-selective feedback can improve coupling efficiency in reactive systems compared to stationary excitation.

## Expected Effects

- Reduced phase variance
- Increased impedance stability
- Improved consistency of power transfer

## Application Hypothesis (Electrolysis)

In electrochemical systems, SRC may:

- reduce bubble-induced losses
- improve electrode surface utilization
- reduce effective overpotential
- stabilize operation under dynamic conditions

## Null Hypothesis

No measurable difference between structured and conventional excitation.

## Evaluation Criteria

- Gas production vs input power
- Phase stability over time
- Impedance behavior
- Thermal behavior

All effects are expected to remain within classical physical constraints.
